challenge.referenceSolution:
#include <experimental/simd>
#include <array>
#include <print>
namespace stdx = std::experimental;

float dot_product_simd(const float* a, const float* b) {
    stdx::fixed_size_simd<float, 4> va, vb;
    va.copy_from(a, stdx::element_aligned);
    vb.copy_from(b, stdx::element_aligned);
    return stdx::reduce(va * vb);
}

int main() {
    std::array<float,4> a = {1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f, 4.0f};
    std::array<float,4> b = {4.0f, 3.0f, 2.0f, 1.0f};
    std::println("{}", dot_product_simd(a.data(), b.data()));
}

lessons.theory:
Note: `std::linalg` (P1673) is part of the C++26 standard but has not yet been implemented by GCC or Clang. Code examples follow the specification.

## Design philosophy

`std::linalg` is **not a matrix class**. It is a set of free functions that operate on `std::mdspan` views over your storage. You create a `std::vector`, `std::array`, or raw buffer yourself, wrap it in an `mdspan`, and pass it to linalg functions. No hidden allocations.

```cpp
#include <linalg>
#include <mdspan>
#include <vector>

std::vector<double> buf = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6};
auto A = std::mdspan(buf.data(), 2, 3);  // 2×3, row-major
// A[0,0]=1  A[0,1]=2  A[0,2]=3
// A[1,0]=4  A[1,1]=5  A[1,2]=6
```

## Key types and memory layout

```cpp
// Static extents (known at compile time)
std::mdspan<double, std::extents<size_t, 3, 4>>  A;  // always 3×4

// Dynamic extents (set at runtime)
std::mdspan<double, std::dextents<size_t, 2>>    B;  // any 2D size

// Mixed: one axis static, one dynamic
std::mdspan<double, std::extents<size_t, 3, std::dynamic_extent>> C;
```

| Policy | Order | Contiguous elements |
|---|---|---|
| `std::layout_right` | row-major (C order) | `A[i, j]` and `A[i, j+1]` |
| `std::layout_left` | column-major (Fortran/BLAS) | `A[i, j]` and `A[i+1, j]` |

System BLAS (MKL, OpenBLAS) expects column-major order. `std::linalg::transposed()` lets you pass a row-major matrix as its transpose without copying data.

## BLAS 1 — vector operations

```cpp
// z = x + y
std::linalg::add(x, y, z);

// x *= alpha (in-place)
std::linalg::scale(alpha, x);

// dot product
double d = std::linalg::dot(x, y);

// Euclidean norm √(Σxᵢ²)
double n2 = std::linalg::vector_norm2(x);

// L1 norm Σ|xᵢ|
double n1 = std::linalg::vector_abs_sum(x);
```

## BLAS 2 — matrix-vector operations

```cpp
// y = A·x (overwrites y)
std::linalg::matrix_vector_product(A, x, y);

// z = alpha * A·x + beta * y
std::linalg::matrix_vector_product(alpha, A, x, beta, y, z);
```

## BLAS 3 — matrix-matrix operations

```cpp
// C = A·B (overwrites C)
std::linalg::matrix_product(A, B, C);
```

## Triangular and symmetric operations

```cpp
// y = triangular_A · x (upper triangle only)
std::linalg::triangular_matrix_vector_product(A, std::linalg::upper_triangle, x, y);

// C += alpha * A·Aᵀ (symmetric rank-k update)
std::linalg::symmetric_matrix_rank_k_update(alpha, A, C);
```

## Lazy view transformations (zero-copy)

Transformation functions return a new `mdspan` with a different mapping or accessor policy — no data copying:

```cpp
auto At  = std::linalg::transposed(A);           // transposed view
auto Ac  = std::linalg::conjugated(A);           // conjugate view (for complex)
auto Acd = std::linalg::conjugate_transposed(A); // A† (Hermitian transpose)
auto sA  = std::linalg::scaled(2.0, A);          // 2·A, read-only
```

`transposed(A)` swaps the extents (`extent(0)` and `extent(1)` are exchanged) and redefines the mapping so that `A[i,j]` and `At[j,i]` address the same cell in memory.

## Accessor policies

Under the hood, lazy views are implemented through `std::mdspan` accessor policies:

- `std::linalg::scaled_accessor<S, NestedAcc>` — multiplies every read by `S`.
- `std::linalg::conjugated_accessor<NestedAcc>` — conjugates every read value.

They compose: `scaled(2.0, conjugated(A))` creates an accessor that reads `2 * conj(A[i,j])` without any intermediate buffers.

## Parallel overloads

```cpp
// parallel execution — same syntax as std::sort and other algorithms
std::linalg::matrix_product(std::execution::par, A, B, C);
```

The same execution policies as `<algorithm>`: `seq`, `par`, `par_unseq`.

## Performance: delegating to system BLAS

The standard permits (and encourages) implementations to delegate calls to the system BLAS — Intel MKL, OpenBLAS, Apple Accelerate. The standard defines the interface; performance is the implementation's responsibility. With column-major data and the correct `layout` policies, there should be no gap compared to direct BLAS calls.

## `std::linalg` vs Eigen

| Criterion | `std::linalg` | Eigen |
|---|---|---|
| Dependencies | none | Eigen only |
| Compatibility | C++26+ | C++14/17 |
| API style | free functions over `mdspan` | `Matrix` class with operators |
| Lazy expression chains | no | expression templates |
| Decompositions (SVD, QR, Cholesky) | no | yes |

Choose `std::linalg` for portability, zero dependencies, and C++26 standard compliance. Choose Eigen for long expression chains like `(A + B * C).transpose()` or built-in matrix decompositions.

